[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing memory support for Android**\n\nI'm wondering if adding long support to Memory will affect Android32 while creating a one-to-one test for Android64. I need to understand how the build runs each test class within the same JVM. For JVM tests, JUnit runs everything in one process, so how does class loading order work? To cover Android64, I’d need to load protobuf classes in an isolated classloader. There might be duplication concerns regarding coverage. I'll need to ensure I write tests outside of the package and stick with public APIs.\n\n**Exploring Android test coverage**\n\nI'm considering whether to use JavaCompiler or tweak libcore.io.Memory to support long and create a new test for Android64 while accepting drops in Android32's previous coverage. Since the user only runs active classes, could that lead to a total failure? They might rerun dynamic coverage, expecting no drops. Changing the static initialization timing could help, but if Memory supports both int and long, Android64 would always be preferred. I might explore running two test tasks in separate JVM forks. I'll check build.gradle for more insights.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_01f9d6b1d9b76f790169f2da6dd4448196abc06c857f18a073\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp8tp0BbdbRZGy6ML3-O38dTKai3snX0w2zmLtflCgLG0BMEZ6viliX1DFiHmzA5dN5p2Dt6UojWRczcEMbQ4B2ukD7u8o56ZSQSWYjhQfCiBB2B3RLEmG_2M8tfDZvgtaXtNXNip5hzwhnrzD-qork87dajNn_GoWtY8AebgKj9kowGPct-oGNj3FstU_1dWV5aDtKUZkxcI9ND-RMCypVFcapdEc1e5FRFctgvqvYU2mHtga3X534P8FPf-g6VFGPokDoboJvMNphajIqtMwcMC8vS2A1Dm9INm9R3G4Oz7K8o1Q97UJn9uEtS89d69reykXhc3JqK_s4fYpid9PsrqObjSFNQJjBJRuicXYuoj6e66y1muH2ielwG-QJVv-Tr8RS-j33KSGz9obE_rW1GdQiKwVE5OHM8sartbHqcfKQvPL3efclePSPnEf5Y5E82lF019ixW8-O8baTnG1f_WmvBjrk6pQhXOFPlzWL24pT7hSjICY47wNCycbRSwaYJf-QwsExYMdN1lhmcivD_q7uuXKtMQ0S33ZCiyyhXMgersoq0R58jyVJPDDrnZK_vDO_CM6ib_9IxY_JEIviVA8QuV0j